column1: This is the most recent readme publication based on all site-date combinations used during stackByTable.
Information specific to the query, including sites and dates, has been removed. The remaining content reflects general metadata for the data product.
All files used during stacking are listed at the bottom of this document, which includes the data publication dates.

This data package been produced by and downloaded from the National Ecological Observatory Network, managed cooperatively by Battelle. These data are provided under the terms of the NEON data policy at http://data.neonscience.org/data-policy.

Description: Precipitation is observed using one of two sensors. Primary precipitation is observed using a weighing gauge housed within a small double fence intercomparison reference, which is generally located within 0.5 km of the tower infrastructure. Secondary precipitation is observed using a tipping bucket located on the top of the tower infrastructure. Ground level precipitation (also known as throughfall) is also observed using tipping buckets at 3 of 5 soil array locations. Bulk precipitation is determined at five- and thirty-minute intervals for primary precipitation and at one- and thirty-minute intervals for secondary precipitation. AIS sites only include Primary (DFIR at Core Aquatic sites; currently only 2 or 3) or Secondary (tipping buckets at relocatable sites; currently about 8). No AIS

Abstract: Across NEON sites two methods will be used to determine bulk precipitation. Bulk precipitation measurements at core sites consist of a weighing gauge surrounded by a double fence inter-comparison reference (DFIR). Bulk precipitation measurements at relocatable sites are made with a tipping bucket. Bulk precipitation measured using a DFIR and a weighing gauge is known to provide improved results over tipping bucket measurements. Thus, the weighing gauge surrounded by the DFIR is considered the “primary” method, while the tipping bucket is referred to as the “secondary” method.
Data collected in any given month are published during the second full week of the following month.

Brief Design Description: Primary precipitation will be measured by a weighing gauge surrounded by a small double fence inter-comparison reference (DFIR) at all core terrestrial sites.  Secondary precipitation will be measured by a tipping bucket at all terrestrial relocatable sites, a select number of terrestrial core sites, and at aquatic sites.  Throughfall will be measured by a tipping bucket equipped with troughs (extending outward from the tipping bucket) at all terrestrial sites where the canopy is seasonally taller than the height of the throughfall collectors' inlets.
Brief Study Area Description: Some form of precipitation data are collected at all NEON terrestrial and aquatic sites.

Sensor(s): Belfort AEPG II 600M weighing gauge (primary precipitation), Met One 372 tipping bucket (non-heated; secondary precipitation and throughfall) and 379 tipping bucket (heated; secondary precipitation)
Keywords: secondary precipitation, precipitation, primary precipitation, tipping bucket, bulk precipitation, throughfall, interception, snowfall, rainfall, tower, snow
This data product contains up to 6 data tables:
SECPRE_1min - Secondary Precipitation pooled over 1 minute
SECPRE_30min - Secondary Precipitation pooled over 30 minutes
PRIPRE_5min - Primary Precipitation pooled over 5 minutes
PRIPRE_30min - Primary Precipitation pooled over 30 minutes
If data are unavailable for the particular sites and dates queried, some tables may be absent.
Basic download package definition: Includes the data product, summary statistics, expanded uncertainty, and final quality flag.
Expanded download package definition: Includes the basic package information plus quality metrics for all of the quality assessment and quality control analyses.

NEON data files are named using a series of component abbreviations separated by periods. File naming conventions for NEON data files differ between NEON science teams. A file will have the same name whether it is accessed via the data portal or the API.
The definitions of component abbreviations are below. See NEON.DOC.002651: NEON Data Product Numbering Convention, located at http://data.neonscience.org/documents for more information.
General conventions, used for all data products:

NEON: denotes the organizational origin of the data product and identifies the product as operational; data collected as part of a special data collection exercise are designated by a separate, unique alphanumeric code created by the PI.
DOM: a three-character alphanumeric code, referring to the domain of data acquisition (D01 - D20).
SITE: a four-character alphanumeric code, referring to the site of data acquisition; all sites are designated by a standardized four-character alphabetic code.
DPL: a three-character alphanumeric code, referring to data product processing level;
PRNUM: a five-character numeric code, referring to the data product number (see the Data Product Catalog at http://data.neonscience.org/data-product-catalog).

REV: a three-digit designation, referring to the revision number of the data product. The REV value is incremented by 1 each time a major change is made in instrumentation, data collection protocol, or data processing such that data from the preceding revision is not directly comparable to the new.

HOR: a three-character designation, referring to measurement locations within one horizontal plane. For example, if five surface measurements were taken, one at each of the five soil array plots, the number in the HOR field would range from 001-005.

VER: a three-character designation, referring to measurement locations within one vertical plane. For example, if eight air temperature measurements are collected, one at each tower vertical level, the number in the VER field would range from 010-080. If five soil temperature measurements are collected below the soil surface, the number in the VER field would range from 501-505.

TMI: a three-character designation, referring to the temporal representation, averaging period, or coverage of the data product (e.g., minute, hour, month, year, sub-hourly, day, lunar month, single instance, seasonal, annual, multi-annual). 000 = native resolution, 001 = native resolution (variable or regular) or 1 minute, 002 = 2 minute, 005 = 5 minute, 015 = 15 minute, 030 = 30 minute, 060 = 60 minutes or 1 hour, 100 = approximately once per minute at stream sites and once every 5-10 minutes at buoy sites (lakes/rivers), 101-103 = native resolution of replicate sensor 1, 2, and 3 respectively, 999 = Sensor conducts measurements at varied interval depending on air mass, 01D = 1 day, 01M = 1 month, 01Y = 1 year.
DESC: an abbreviated description of the data file or table.
YYYY-MM: the year and month of the data in the file.
PKGTYPE: the type of data package downloaded. Options are 'basic', representing the basic download package, or 'expanded',representing the expanded download package (see more information below).
GENTIME: the date-time stamp when the file was generated, in UTC. The format of the date-time stamp is YYYYMMDDTHHmmSSZ.
YY: Year, last two digits only
T: Indicator that the time stamp is beginning
Z: Universal Time Coordinated (Universal Coordinated Time), or UTC

Issue: False throughfall sensor tips recorded.
Issue: Throughfall tipping bucket stopped functioning and recording tips.
Issue: Belfort gauge temporarily out of commission.
Issue: Secondary precip bucket not functioning.
Issue: Multiple issues encountered with primary precipitation sensor including snow cap and false recording.
Issue: Heater for secondary precipitation non-operational, causing snow accumulation in bucket and lagged and/or missed precipitation event recordings.
Resolution: Heater repaired. Manual flagging applied during affected date range.

Issue: The alter shield around the primary precipitation sensor was stabilized to investigate unusual signals in the sensor raw data. This may have impacted data quality relating to precipitation events during this time, particularly during windy conditions.
Resolution: The stabilization of the alter shield around the primary precipitation sensor was stopped.

Issue: The alter shield around the primary precipitation sensor was removed to investigate unusual signals in the sensor raw data. This may have impacted data quality relating to precipitation events during this time, particularly during windy conditions.
Resolution: The alter shield was reinstalled. Data were flagged.
Issue: The Primary Precipitation DFIR failed calibration after emptying.
Resolution: Sensor passed calibration and manual flagging was applied.

Issue: Throughfall data and associated quality flags should be considered unreliable and of limited use. The sensor frequently becomes blocked with debris and the tipping mechanism frequently falls off its rocker, causing precipitation events to go unrecorded.

Resolution: Ongoing. Additional screens were added to the collection troughs to minimize the amount of debris entering the sensor in fall 2017. A more robust design of the tipping mechanism is currently in production and all sensors will be retrofitted. Data were manually flagged.
Issue: False Secondary Precipitation tip recorded due to cleaning.
Issue: Primary precipitation sensor failed calibration.
Resolution: Sensor re-calibrated. Manual flagging applied in interval between failed and successful calibration.
Issue: During rain events, Secondary Precipitation not streaming tips when Throughfall recording tips.
Issue: Secondary Precipitation sensor only intermittently recording tips and missed events when there was Throughfall data.
Issue: False tip recorded for Secondary Precipitation sensor.
Issue: Sensor not re-calibrated after Ermine fell into DFIR and was removed with some fluid.
Location(s) Affected: TOOL Primary Precipitation sensor (HOR.VER 900.000)
Resolution: Sensor re-calibrated and manual flagging applied.
Issue: Secondary precipitation sensor not registering tips during high precipitation events due to debris.
Issue: Tipping mechanism for Secondary precipitation sensor malfunctioned.
Resolution: Applied manual flagging. Fixed tipping mechanism.
Issue: Throughfall sensor not functioning and recording tips.
Issue: Throughfall sensor clogged and false tips recorded.
Resolution: Sensor cleaned and applied manual flagging.
Issue: Throughfall locations were swapped in database
Location(s) Affected: D11 CLBJ soil plots 3 and 4 (HOR.VER: 003.000, 004.000)
Issue: Throughfall sensor clogged and not recording precipitation events.
Resolution: Sensor cleaned and applied manual flagging.
Issue: Tipping mechanism on secondary precipitation sensor not functioning and recording events.
Resolution: Fixed sensor and applied manual flagging.
Resolution: Re-calibrated sensor and applied manual flagging.
Issue: False tips recorded for secondary precipitation sensor.
Issue: Bad calibration data for DFIR.
Issue: Incorrect calibration information was applied to data for some sites and time periods.
Resolution: Data reprocessed with correct calibration information.
Issue: Secondary precipitation sensor not recording tips and missed events when throughfall data recorded.
Issue: Data suspect due to snow drifting of the DFIR.
Issue: False tips recorded for secondary precipitation and soil plot 5 throughfall sensors.
Location(s) Affected: UKFS (HOR.VERs: 000.060 (secondary precip) and 005.000 (SP5 throughfall))
Issue: Throughfall sensor only intermittently recording tips and missed events when there was other throughfall precipitation data.
Issue: Throughfall sensor powered down for leveling.
Issue: Primary precipitation sensor streaming uncalibrated data.
Issue: Dead frog found in primary precipitation sensor.
Resolution: Applied manual flagging. Sensor recalibrated.
Issue: Incorrect calibration file applied to primary precipitation data resulting in data to be over-flagged.
Resolution: Correct calibration applied and data reprocessed.
Issue: Intermittent power failures caused unreliable data collection
Location(s) Affected: D16 ABBY soil plot 5 (HOR.VER: 005.000)
Issue: Tree fell on sensor impacting data collection area.
Issue: suspected clogged throughfall precipitation resulting in inconsistent readings compared to other sensors
Issue: suspected sensor malfunction resulting in zero precipitation inconsistent with soil moisture data
Issue: Tree fall hit throughfall collector trough knocking it out of alignment.
Location(s) Affected: D16 WREF soil plot 5 (HOR.VER: 005.000)
Issue: Communication failure caused inaccurate readings
Issue: Earthquakes in region caused rain water to spill and data total accumulation data to become inaccurate
Issue: Earthquakes in region caused sensors to become unstable
Issue: Sensor Cable found unplugged, rain events  were missed
Resolution: Sensor cable plugged in and manual flagging applied.

Issue: The alpha and beta quality metric multipliers used for computing the final quality flag were swapped in processing. The final quality flag is raised when alphaQM*m + betaQM*n >= 20%. The multiplier m should be set to 2 and n should be set to 1, but these values were swapped, making it slightly harder to raise the final quality flag. These multipliers were corrected in data produced after the resolution date. Data prior to the resolution date will be reprocessed prior to the first NEON data release. An additional changelog comment will be entered at that time.
Location(s) Affected: All primary precip locations
2020-06-10: All data reprocessed with corrected algorithm.
Issue: Throughfall sensors were removed for a fire, but due to COVID-19 closure field staff were unable to return them to the field post burn.
Resolution: Data redacted until sensors can be returned to their locations.
Issue: Primary Precipitation sensor was shut down and covered because it could not be calibrated due to COVID-19 related halt to field work.
Resolution: Data flagged between time sensor was covered and when it was powered down.
Issue: Loss of power, causing tipping bucket data to populate at potentially false zeros.
Issue: Likely sensor malfunction causing large spans of zeros in dataset

Issue: All data were reprocessed with the most recent algorithms, quality control thresholds, and/or other metadata to improve overall data coverage and quality. Notes have been added to the logs of previously identified issues that have been corrected.

Issue: Spurious trace precipitation is recorded frequently for all primary precipitation sensors (weighing gauges). While actual precipitation events are typically distinguishable from spurious events in the time series, the spurious events can add significantly to precipitation totals when aggregated over long intervals.  Sums of spurious precipitation range from < 0.05 mm/day to > 0.5mm/day, with higher sums generally corresponding to sites and time periods of greater evaporative demand.
Location(s) Affected: All primary precipitation locations.

Resolution: Issue ongoing. We are working on additional quality control algorithms in order to detect and remove spurious trace events in the primary precipitation data product. An updated algorithm is expected sometime in 2021.
Resolution: Data redacted until sensor can be replaced
Issue: Secondary precipitation heater cable was found to be impacting sensor measurements. Date of impact was difficult to determine, so data was cautiously flagged from date of install of sensor
Resolution: Flagging applied from data of sensor install to date of fix.
Issue: During COVID-19 shutdown sensor filled with flying ants that likely manipulated precipitation measurement. This is a recurring issue with the sensor at this site.
Resolution: Unit cleaned and data manually flagged.
Issue: Secondary Precipitation sensor not recording precipitation events reflected in changes in surface water pressure.
Resolution: Sensor manually tested and flagging applied.

KNOWN ISSUE 2018-04-04: All current and previous throughfall precipitation data should be considered unreliable and of limited use. The tipping mechanism frequently falls off its rocker, causing precipitation events to go unrecorded. A more robust design of the tipping mechanism is currently in production and all sensors will be retrofitted. All throughfall precipitation data will be quality flagged as suspect until the sensor retrofit is complete.

KNOWN ISSUE 2020-06-10: A review of the precipitation data product (part of DP1.00006.001) identified that spurious trace precipitation is recorded frequently for all primary precipitation sensors. While actual precipitation events are typically distinguishable from spurious events in the time series, the presence of spurious trace precipitation can add significantly to precipitation totals when aggregated over long intervals.  Sums of spurious precipitation range from < 0.05 mm/day to > 0.5mm/day, with higher sums generally corresponding to sites and time periods of greater evaporative demand.  We are working on additional quality control algorithms in order to detect and remove spurious trace events in the primary precipitation data product. An updated algorithm is expected sometime in 2021.
NEON DATA POLICY AND CITATION GUIDELINES
Please visit http://data.neonscience.org/data-policy for more information about NEON's data policy and citation guidelines.

The data contained in this file are considered provisional. Updates to the data, QA/QC and/or processing algorithms over time will occur on an as-needed basis.  Please check back to this site for updates tracked in change logs.  Query reproducibility on provisional data cannot be guaranteed.

Starting in 2020 or earlier, NEON will begin to offer static versions of each data product, annotated with a globally unique identifier. Versioned IS and OS data will be produced by reprocessing each IS and OS data product from the beginning of the data collection period to approximately 12-18 months prior to the reprocessing date (to allow for calibration checks, return of external lab data, etc.). The reprocessing step will use the most recent QA/QC methods and processing algorithms. Versioned AOP data will be produced by reprocessing the entire AOP archive as advances in algorithms and processing technology are incorporated. This will typically occur in the northern winter months, between flight season peaks, and will be on the order of every 3 to 5 years in frequency.
